). 8.0 mm long. Colour: as for male except for brown flagellar segments, abdominal ventrites pale brown, V5 paler across posterior margin, V6 entirely pale except for brown laterally reflexed margins and very narrowly brown posterior margin; V7 pale in anteromedian portion; abdominal tergites light brown except for tT7, 8 which are darker than rest. Abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[1025,1125,1791,1815]" captionStart="FIGURES 154–159" captionStartId="77.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1516]" captionTargetId="figure-182@77.[151,1436,193,1518]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 154–159. Medeopteryx spp. female abdomens ventral (not to scale) (ANIC). 154 M. antennata. 155 M. corusca (mating pair Catherine Mission). 156 M. cribellata (G381 mating pair). 157 M. effulgens (Kah New Ireland). 158 M. flagrans (G535). M. fulminea (Kar Kar Island)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265404" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265404/files/figure.png" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Fig. 154</figureCitation>
): V6 posterior margin with posterolateral corners acute, broadly excavated across posterior margin with small pointed projection in median line; V8 not indented in median line. Bursa (
<figureCitation box="[655,755,1863,1887]" captionStart="FIGURES 160–167" captionStartId="78.[151,263,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[177,1421,182,1849]" captionTargetId="figure-96@78.[177,1421,181,1849]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURES 160–167. Female Medeopteryx spp. bursa. 160 Medeopteryx antennata female of mating pair Sek Bridge (ANIC). 161, 162 M. corusca female of mating pair Kondiu (ANIC). 163 M. cribellata Kar Kar Island (ANIC). 164–167 M. similispupillae sp. nov. 164 bursa ventral; 165 reproductive system excluding ovaries lateral; 166 median oviduct plate ventral (anterior end to foot of page); 167 anterior plate lateral. Figure legends: 1 median oviduct plate; 2 posterior bursa plate; 3 anterior bursa plate; 4 spermatophore digesting gland." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265408" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265408/files/figure.png" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Fig. 160</figureCitation>
): two sets of separate plates with very small median oviduct sclerite.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="84" lastPageNumber="85" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="83.[151,1436,1395,2032]" lastBlockId="84.[151,1436,151,752]" lastPageId="84" lastPageNumber="85" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1936,1960]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Remarks.</emphasis>
Olivier named this species for the distinctive orange FS, and brown scape and pedicel. A 
<typeStatus box="[1333,1435,1935,1959]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">lectotype</typeStatus>
male and a female (
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; McLean, M. R." box="[379,711,1972,1996]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="223 - 305" refId="ref122809" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; McLean, M. R. (1970) Revisional studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae: Luciolini). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 96, 223 - 305." type="journal article" year="1970">Ballantyne &amp; McLean, 1970</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A." box="[725,935,1972,1996]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="117 - 170" refId="ref122195" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. (1987 a) Further Revisional Studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 113, 117 - 170." type="journal article" year="1987">Ballantyne, 1987a</bibRefCitation>
), and a further male and 
<specimenCount box="[1227,1366,1972,1996]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" type="female">two females</specimenCount>
listed above, are the only specimens LB has seen with the pale coloured FS, consistent with the original description. All are from the type locality of the Fly River. All other specimens assigned have brown FS. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; McLean, M. R." pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="223 - 305" refId="ref122809" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; McLean, M. R. (1970) Revisional studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae: Luciolini). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 96, 223 - 305." type="journal article" year="1970">Ballantyne and McLean (1970:240</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[280,347,188,212]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–5" captionStartId="10.[151,263,1921,1944]" captionTargetBox="[290,1309,181,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-108@10.[282,1309,173,1922]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 3–5. Majority rule tree for the complete analysis of the Luciolinae. Analysis consisted of consensus of 169 MPTs with a length of 5609 from a data set of 143 taxa and 436 morphological characters in (see Table 3). Figure 3, part 1: nodes 1– 34; 4, part 2 Nodes 35–52; 5, part 3 nodes 55–76. Nodes (red). New genera, new species, and still undescribed species in red and bold, with identification numbers blue. Black values above branches show the % of MPTs over 50 %." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265348" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265348/files/figure.png" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) described 
<specimenCount box="[479,566,188,212]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="male">2 males</specimenCount>
with brownish orange FS (from Milne Bay area in Eastern 
<collectingRegion box="[1242,1313,188,211]" country="Indonesia" name="Papua Barat" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Papua</collectingRegion>
, and River Tor in 
<collectingCountry box="[225,334,223,247]" name="Indonesia" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
<collectingRegion box="[340,413,223,247]" country="Indonesia" name="Papua Barat" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Papua</collectingRegion>
), as 
<emphasis box="[462,695,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<taxonomicName box="[462,691,225,248]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pteroptyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antennata">Pteroptyx antennata</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and another 
<specimenCount box="[840,926,223,247]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="male">4 males</specimenCount>
(as &quot;Species A&quot;, page 266) which conformed to 
<taxonomicName box="[181,322,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pteroptyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antennata">
<emphasis box="[181,322,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">P. antennata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except for the uniformly dark FS. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A." box="[719,935,260,284]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="117 - 170" refId="ref122195" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. (1987 a) Further Revisional Studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 113, 117 - 170." type="journal article" year="1987">Ballantyne (1987a)</bibRefCitation>
designated a 
<typeStatus box="[1092,1194,260,284]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">lectotype</typeStatus>
male from a 
<typeStatus box="[1349,1436,260,284]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">syntype</typeStatus>
series from the type locality and assigned a further 
<specimenCount box="[730,830,295,319]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="male">23 males</specimenCount>
to the species and included Ballantyne and McLean's Species A; all conformed to the description of 
<taxonomicName box="[690,802,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pteroptyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antennata">
<emphasis box="[690,802,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">antennata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; McLean, M. R." box="[842,1199,332,356]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="223 - 305" refId="ref122809" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; McLean, M. R. (1970) Revisional studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae: Luciolini). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 96, 223 - 305." type="journal article" year="1970">Ballantyne and McLean (1970)</bibRefCitation>
(i.e. all lacked paler coloured FS), and many had flashing data associated (
<bibRefCitation author="Lloyd, J. E." box="[755,903,367,391]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="991 - 1008" refId="ref127038" refString="Lloyd, J. E. (1973 a) Fireflies of Melanesia: Bioluminescence, Mating Behavior, and Synchronous flashing. Environmental Entomology, 2 (no. 6), 991 - 1008." type="journal article" year="1973">Lloyd 1973a</bibRefCitation>
). When observed with the unaided eye the dark and shiny brown scape and pedicel, and dull lighter brown FS approach Olivier's original description.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="84.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<bibRefCitation author="Lloyd, J. E." box="[199,362,439,463]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="991 - 1008" refId="ref127038" refString="Lloyd, J. E. (1973 a) Fireflies of Melanesia: Bioluminescence, Mating Behavior, and Synchronous flashing. Environmental Entomology, 2 (no. 6), 991 - 1008." type="journal article" year="1973">Lloyd (1973a)</bibRefCitation>
described the two major flash patterns of the males and the ability of small groups of flying males to flash in &quot;apparent synchrony.&quot; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lloyd, J. E." box="[603,765,476,500]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="268 - 270" refId="ref127075" refString="Lloyd, J. E. (1973 b) Model for the mating protocol of synchronously flashing fireflies. Nature, 245 (no. 5423), 268 - 270. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1038 / 245268 a 0" type="journal article" year="1973">Lloyd (1973b)</bibRefCitation>
described and figured the &quot;four modulation flicker&quot;; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lloyd, J. E." pageId="84" pageNumber="85" refId="ref127164" refString="Lloyd, J. E. (1978) Insect Bioluminescence. In Herring, P. J. (Ed.) Bioluminescence in Action. New York. Academic Press, 570 pp." type="book" year="1978">Lloyd (1978)</bibRefCitation>
figured &quot;one of two flicker patterns” and (1979) the flash pattern of Species F (assigned to 
<taxonomicName box="[1287,1399,513,536]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pteroptyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antennata">
<emphasis box="[1287,1399,513,536]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">antennata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A." box="[151,369,548,572]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="117 - 170" refId="ref122195" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. (1987 a) Further Revisional Studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 113, 117 - 170." type="journal article" year="1987">Ballantyne (1987a)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="84.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<bibRefCitation author="Guerin-Meneville, F. E." box="[199,483,583,607]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" refId="ref125132" refString="Guerin-Meneville, F. E. (1838) Insectes. In: Lesson, M. (Ed.) Voyage autour du monde, execute par ordre du roi, sur la corvette de sa majeste, La Coquille, pendant les annees 1822, 1823, 1824, et 1825 etc. Zool. 2, Pt. 2, Div. 1, Ch. xiii. Bertrand: Paris, pp. 57 - 302." type="journal volume" year="1838">Guérin-Méneville (1838)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName box="[608,804,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruficollis">
<emphasis box="[608,804,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Luciola ruficollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with black antennae, abdomen entirely yellow beneath and abdominal apex &quot;trilobo''. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A." box="[506,724,620,644]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="117 - 170" refId="ref122195" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. (1987 a) Further Revisional Studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 113, 117 - 170." type="journal article" year="1987">Ballantyne (1987a)</bibRefCitation>
considered 
<taxonomicName box="[865,966,620,644]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruficollis">
<emphasis box="[865,966,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">ruficollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have been based on 
<taxonomicName box="[1272,1384,621,644]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pteroptyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antennata">
<emphasis box="[1272,1384,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">antennata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
like specimens. 
<taxonomicName box="[281,475,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ruficollis">
<emphasis box="[281,475,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Luciola ruficollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not presently identified in collections of New Guinean 
<emphasis box="[1124,1217,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laporte. Laporte" authorityYear="1833" box="[1124,1213,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Luciola</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="84.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
At Alexishafen 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin" baseAuthorityYear="2013" box="[381,649,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Medeopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antennata">
<emphasis box="[381,649,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Medeopteryx antennata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sympatric with, and similar to 
<emphasis box="[1042,1273,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<taxonomicName authorityName="MPP" baseAuthorityName="Ballantyne" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[1042,1269,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Medeopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similisantennata">M. similisantennata</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
with which it apparently shares the same pattern of light production. The similarities in light patterns suggest a form of mimicry.
</paragraph>
